I'll provide a small example in Verilog:

```verilog
module if_logic_example (
  input wire [2:0] select,
  input wire [7:0] a, b, c, d,
  output wire [7:0] out
);

  // Using if-else statement for simple 4-to-1 multiplexer
  always @(*) begin
    if (select == 3'b000) begin
      out = a;
    end else if (select == 3'b001) begin
      out = b;
    end else if (select == 3'b010) begin
      out = c;
    end else begin
      out = d;
    end
  end

endmodule
```

In this example, we have a simple 4-to-1 multiplexer. The `select` signal chooses which of the 4 inputs (a, b, c, or d) will be assigned to the output `out`. The if-else statement checks the value of `select` and sets the output accordingly.

